amworth, Staffordshire, England":"Tamworth, Staffordshire, England","Europe":"Europe","France":"France","Vassy, Calvados, Basse-Normandie, FRANCE":"Vassy, Calvados, Lower Normandy, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"HARCOUET","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin) and French: habitational name from any of the places in Eure and Calvados named Harcourt, from Old French <i>cour(t)</i> ‘court, farmyard’ (see   Court  ) with an obscure first element. This surname is very rare in France.","English: habitational name from either of two places in Shropshire named Harcourt. The one near Cleobury Mortimer gets the name from Old English <i>heafocere</i> ‘hawker, falconer’ + <i>cot</i> ‘hut, cottage’; the one near Wem has as its first element Old English <i>hearpere</i> (see   Harper  ).","History: The surname of French origin (see 1 above) is listed along with the equally rare or even extinct variants or altered forms <i>Haraucourt</i>, <i>Herancourt</i>, and <i>Héraucourt</i> in the (US) National Huguenot Society's register of qualified Huguenot ancestors."],"variants":[{"name":"Court","meanings":["English: topographic or occupational name from Middle English <i>curt</i>, <i>court</i> ‘large house’ (a word of the same ultimately Latin origin as 2 below), denoting someone who lived or worked in a manor house or castle, a courtly retainer.","French: topographic name from Old French <i>co(u)rt</i> ‘court, farmyard’ (from Latin <i>cohors</i>, <i>cors</i>, genitive <i>cohortis</i>, <i>cortis</i> ‘court, farmyard, enclosure’).","English and French: nickname for a physically small man, or ironically for a large man, from the adjective Middle English <i>curt</i>, Old French <i>co(u)rt</i> ‘short, small’ (from Latin <i>curtus</i> ‘curtailed, truncated, cut short, broken off’). Compare French   Lecourt  ."]}]},{"name":"Mathilde","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’."],"variants":[{"name":"Mechtild","meanings":["from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’."]},{"name":"Matilda","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."]},{"name":"Mechtilde","meanings":["from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’."]}]},{"name":"Mabille","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Elaborated form of   Mabel  , under the influence of the French phrase <i>ma belle</i> ‘my beautiful one’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Mathilde Mabille de HARCOUET was born about 1168, in France, her father, Rollon de HARCOUET, was 31 and her mother, Blanche de DOL, was 17. She had at least 2 daughters with Philippe II de Vassy. She died on 8 January 1234, in Vassy, Calvados, Lower Normandy, France, at the age of 67."},"et":{"about 1168–08 JAN 1234":"umbes 1168–8. jaanuar 1234","1168–1234":"1168–1234","1155–1250":"1155–1250","1180–Female":"1180–Surnud","1190–1271":"1190–1271","1138–1203":"1138–1203","1152–Female":"1152–Surnud","1190":"1190","08 JAN 1234":"8. jaanuar 1234","about 1190":"umbes 1190","1152":"1152","1250":"1250","1271":"1271","1180":"1180","1138":"1138","Cir 1180":"1180","1203":"1203","8 Jan 1203":"8. jaanuar 1203","1234":"1234","1168":"1168","1155":"1155","about 1168":"umbes 1168","Of, Tamworth, Staffordshire, England":"Tamworth, Staffordshire, England","Europe":"Europe","France":"Prantsusmaa","Vassy, Calvados, Basse-Normandie, FRANCE":"Vassy, Calvados, Basse-Normandie, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"about 1168–08 JAN 1234":"noin 1168–8. tammikuuta 1234","1168–1234":"1168–1234","1155–1250":"1155–1250","1180–Female":"1180–Kuollut","1190–1271":"1190–1271","1138–1203":"1138–1203","1152–Female":"1152–Kuollut","1190":"1190","08 JAN 1234":"8. tammikuuta 1234","about 1190":"noin 1190","1152":"1152","1250":"1250","1271":"1271","1180":"1180","1138":"1138","Cir 1180":"1180","1203":"1203","8 Jan 1203":"8. tammikuuta 1203","1234":"1234","1168":"1168","1155":"1155","about 1168":"noin 1168","Of, Tamworth, Staffordshire, England":"Tamworth, Staffordshire, England","Europe":"Europe","France":"Ranska","Vassy, Calvados, Basse-Normandie, FRANCE":"Vassy, Calvados, Basse-Normandie, Ranska"},"fr":{"about 1168–08 JAN 1234":"environ 1168–8 janvier 1234","1168–1234":"1168–1234","1155–1250":"1155–1250","1180–Female":"1180–Décédée","1190–1271":"1190–1271","1138–1203":"1138–1203","1152–Female":"1152–Décédée","1190":"1190","08 JAN 1234":"8 janvier 1234","about 1190":"environ 1190","1152":"1152","1250":"1250","1271":"1271","1180":"1180","1138":